  "lesson_id": "lesson_kireji_kana",
  "lesson_title": "The Poetic Sigh: Mastering the Exclamatory 'Kana' (かな)",
  "lesson_summary": "This lesson introduces 'kana', a terminal particle known as a 'kireji' (cutting word) that acts as an emotional exclamation mark, signaling a moment of deep realization or wonder.",
  "grammar_point": "kireji_kana",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "The particle かな (kana) is used at the end of a poem to express a sigh of emotion, admiration, or poignant realization. In programming terms, it is like an 'EOF' (End of File) marker that also carries an emotional metadata tag. In Classical Chinese, it functions similarly to the exclamatory particles '哉' (zāi) or '也' (yě) used to conclude a thought with emphasis.",
    "formation": "It typically follows a Noun or a Verb/Auxiliary in its Rentaikei (Attributive) form.",
    "variations": [
      "Often appears as '...nuru kana' (has become...!) or '...keri kana' (alas, I realize...!)."
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "Do not confuse with the modern Japanese 'kana' which expresses doubt or uncertainty ('I wonder?'). In classical poetry, it is almost always a definitive exclamation of feeling."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "Having explored how particles link nouns and how auxiliaries modify time, we now reach the 'emotional terminal.' In classical poetry, the poet often needs a way to 'cut' the flow of the poem and let the accumulated emotion resonate. This is the role of the kireji (切れ字). Think of 'kana' as a linguistic sigh—a way to say 'Ah, it is so!' or 'How beautiful/sad it is!'"
    },
